<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">USING PAY TO ENCOURAGE PUBLIC SERVICE  <span class="divider"> | </span></span> A recent letter sent to the boards of Wall Streetâs biggest banks has created quite a stir within the halls of banks and parts of corporate America, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/01/encouraging-public-service-through-the-revolving-door">Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook Column</a></b>. The letter, sent by Heather Slavkin Corzo, director of the A.F.L.-C.I.O.âs office of investment, asked why banks routinely pay out special compensation packages to executives who leave to take government jobs when those packages were intended to retain them. But perhaps the A.F.L.-C.I.O. has it backward, Mr. Sorkin writes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At issue is a debate about the Wall Street practice of <b>accelerating the vesting of restricted shares and deferred compensation</b> to executives who leave for a role in government. Usually, executives who leave for another job elsewhere, or decide to retire early, forfeit such payments, which act as an incentive to stay and a penalty for departing. The issue moved into the headlines recently when Antonio F. Weiss, a Lazard banker who has been nominated for under secretary of the Treasury for domestic finance, disclosed that his firm would pay him about $20 million in stock and deferred compensation if he were to win confirmation. Mr. Weiss would not be entitled to that money if he were to leave the firm for a rival bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">â<b>While this topic may make for juicy headlines</b> about the ârevolving door,â the A.F.L.-C.I.O. and others seem to be deliberately overlooking important issues, and the entire debate appears to be based more on a populist shakedown than on good public policy,â Mr. Sorkin writes. (The Washington Postâs Editorial Board similarly called the fight against Mr. Weiss &#8220;<b><a href="//www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/antonio-weiss-deserves-a-fair-nomination-hearing/2014/11/29/2ff9dd3c-7728-11e4-a755-e32227229e7b_story.html">a populist witch hunt</a></b>.â) These compensation policies, Mr. Sorkin adds, allow our most highly qualified employees from the private sector to pursue public service. âIt is hard enough finding people in the private sector willing to go through the gauntlet that public service so frequently entails,â Mr. Sorkin writes. âLetâs not make it harder.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">WEB THIEVES ZERO IN ON BIOTECH <span class="divider"> | </span></span> A new breed of cybercriminal is on the loose. For more than a year, a group of web thieves has been stealing email correspondence from more than 100 organizations â most of them publicly traded health care or pharmaceutical companies â apparently in pursuit of information significant enough to affect global financial markets, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/12/02/technology/hackers-target-biotech-companies.html">Nicole Perlroth reports in The New York Times</a></b>. The groupâs activities, detailed in a report released on Monday morning by FireEye, a Silicon Valley security company, show criminals intent on using their hacking skills to gain a market edge in the pharmaceutical industry, where news of clinical trials, regulatory decisions or safety or legal issues can significantly affect a companyâs stock price.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The attackers, whom FireEye named âFin4â because they are one of several groups that hack for financial gain, appear to be native English speakers who are <b>well versed in the Wall Street vernacular</b>. Their email lures are precisely tailored toward each victim, written in flawless English and carefully worded to sound as if they were sent by someone with an extensive background in investment banking and with knowledge of the terms those in the industry employ. Different groups of victims â frequently including top-level executives; legal counsel; regulatory, risk and compliance officers; researchers; and scientists â are sent different emails. In several cases, <b>attackers have used confidential company documents</b>, which they had previously stolen, as aids in their deception.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Unlike other well-documented attacks originating in China or Russia, <b>these attackers do not use malware</b> to crawl further and further into an organizationâs computer servers and infrastructure. They simply read a personâs emails and set rules for the infiltrated inboxes to automatically delete any email that contains words such as âhacked,â âphishedâ or âmalware,â to increase the time before their victims learn their accounts have been compromised. FireEye would not name the victims, citing nondisclosure agreements with its clients, but said that all but three of the affected organizations were publicly listed on the New York Stock Exchange or Nasdaq, while the others were listed on exchanges outside the United States.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> LAW SCHOOLS BATTLE FOR TOP STUDENTS <span class="divider"> | </span></span> As competition for the best students increases, law school has become a buyersâ market, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/01/law-school-becomes-buyers-market-as-competition-for-best-students-increases">Elizabeth Olson writes in DealBook</a></b>. Faced with plummeting enrollment and resistance to five-figure student debt, some middle-tier schools are trying to entice new students by reducing or freezing tuition and increasing financial aid. The Roger Williams University School of Law in Bristol, R.I., for instance, cut tuition by 18 percent, to $33,792 from $41,400 through the 2015-16 academic year, and locked in the rate for three years for first-year students.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;<b>Once seen as cash generators</b>, many university-affiliated law schools now lean on their parent institutions to survive a rough period,â Ms. Olson writes. Law school enrollment has been falling because the economic recession has reduced the number of legal jobs. In the economic fallout, law firms began to cut positions and have not restored them, she adds. The number of first-year law school students fell 11 percent in the fall of 2013 from the fall of 2012, part of a 24 percent decline in just three years, according to the American Bar Association. The incoming class in 2013 stood at 39,675 students, the smallest first-year class since the 1970s, when law school enrollment began to rise substantially.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>A big fear for law students</b> is that they will not be able to find a job that pays enough to repay $150,000 to $200,000 in education loans. Indeed, nine months after graduating, only 57 percent of the 2013 graduates had full-time jobs that required passing the bar, according to the American Bar Association. âStudents are voting with their feet, and demanding a better deal,â said Prof. Daniel B. Rodriguez, dean of the Northwestern University School of Law. Although enrollment is increasing at some schools that have lowered tuition, including Roger Williams, it has come with a price, Ms. Olson writes. Skeptics contend that some schools are padding enrollments with students who have <b>lower admissions test scores and college grades</b>.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
