<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Automakers release <b>vehicle sales</b> for November. <b>Gallupâs Economic Confidence Index</b> is released at 8:30 a.m. Data on <b>construction spending</b> comes out at 10 a.m. <b>Stanley Fischer</b>, the Fed vice chairman, speaks on the economic outlook at The Wall Street Journal C.E.O. Council annual meeting at 8:10 a.m. <b>Lael Brainard</b>, a Fed governor, delivers welcome and opening remarks at an outreach meeting of the San Francisco Fedâs Los Angeles branch at 12 p.m. <b>Janet L. Yellen</b>, the Fed chairwoman, gives the welcome remarks before the 2014 College Fed Challenge national finals. <b>Benjamin M. Lawsky</b>, New York Stateâs top banking regulator, is on CNBC at 10 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">LENDING CLUB SETS I.P.O. RANGE <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Lending Club, the leader in the so-called peer-to-peer lending industry, is getting closer to going public. On Monday, the company disclosed that it planned to price its stock sale at $10 to $12 a share, potentially raising up to $692.4 million, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/12/01/lending-club-seeks-up-to-692-million-in-i-p-o">DealBookâs Michael J. de la Merced reports</a></b>. At the midpoint of that range, Lending Club, which already has support from some of the biggest names on Wall Street and Silicon Valley, would be <b>valued at about $4 billion</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAs Lending Club executives hit the road for the next week to meet with potential investors, they are aiming to convince those institutions â including investment arms of some of the banks the company has sought to displace â that the prospects of the peer-to-peer lending industry it helped create are looking brighter than ever,â Mr. de la Merced writes. The company will trade on the New York Stock Exchange, under the ticker symbol âLC.â <b>No other alternative lender trades on the public markets</b>. The initial lenders on the service were individuals, but a significant percentage now are big mutual funds and hedge funds.</p>
</div>
